   <text>
      <body>
         <div>
            <pb facs="#facs_1" n="TLx-0021_p001.jpg" xml:id="img_0001" corresp="https://id.acdh.oeaw.ac.at/tillich-lectures/TLx-0021_p001.jpg"/>
            <p facs="#facs_1_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_1_l" n="N001"/>[1]
               <lb facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_2" n="N002"/>Sculptures and Painting for:
               <lb facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_4" n="N003"/><hi style="text-decoration: underline;"><rs type="keyword" ref="#Religion">Religion</rs> and the Visual <rs type="keyword" ref="#Arts">Arts</rs></hi>
               <lb facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_5" n="N004"/><hi style="text-decoration: underline;">I. The Circle of <rs type="keyword" ref="#Ancient_Greece">Greek Art</rs>:</hi>
               <lb facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_6" n="N005"/>1. Archaic god or goddess. (<rs type="keyword" ref="#Expressionism">Expressionistic</rs>)
               <lb facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_7" n="N006"/>2. Classical god or goddess <hi style="text-decoration: underline;">and</hi> human figure.
               <lb facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_9" n="N007"/>(Idealistic)
               <lb facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_14" n="N008"/>3. <rs type="keyword" ref="#Naturalism">Naturalistic</rs>     "     "     "     "     "     "
               <lb facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_15" n="N009"/>4. Archa-istic Greek: Roman figure or god.
               <lb facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_16" n="N010"/>(<rs type="keyword" ref="#Expressionism">Expressionistic</rs>)
               <lb facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_17" n="N011"/><hi style="text-decoration: underline;">II. Analogies in the West till 1900</hi>
               <lb facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_18" n="N012"/>a] <rs type="keyword" ref="#Expressionism">Expressionistic</rs> predominance
               <lb facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_19" n="N013"/>1. A Catacomb and a Byzantine picture
               <lb facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_20" n="N014"/>(<rs type="keyword" ref="#Ancient_Greece">classical</rs>-idealistic elements)
               <lb facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_21" n="N015"/>2. A Romanesc crucifixion (or similarly ex-
               <lb facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_22" n="N016"/>pressive = distorted.)
            </p>
            <pb facs="#facs_2" n="TLx-0021_p002.jpg" xml:id="img_0002"/>
            <p facs="#facs_2_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_2_l" n="N001"/>[2]
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_1" n="N002"/>3. A Gothic <rs type="keyword" ref="#Religion">religious</rs> sculpture.
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_2" n="N003"/>4. A Francis-scene by <rs type="person" ref="#tillich_person_id__681">Giotto</rs> (Beyond the categories)
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_3" n="N004"/>b] <rs type="keyword" ref="#Naturalism">Naturalistic</rs>-idealistic predominance.
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_4" n="N005"/>1. <rs type="person" ref="#tillich_person_id__3099">Masaccio</rs> or/and <rs type="person" ref="#tillich_person_id__3889">Perugino</rs>
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_5" n="N006"/>2. <rs type="person" ref="#tillich_person_id__3965">Dolci </rs>as "beautifying <rs type="keyword" ref="#Naturalism">naturalism</rs>".
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_6" n="N007"/>3. <rs type="person" ref="#tillich_person_id__3086">Watteau</rs> (or <rs type="person" ref="#tillich_person_id__3966">Fragonard</rs>) as "playing <rs type="keyword" ref="#Naturalism">naturalism</rs>"
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_7" n="N008"/>4. <rs type="person" ref="#tillich_person_id__3967">Caravaggio</rs> as "aggressive <rs type="keyword" ref="#Naturalism">naturalism</rs>".
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_8" n="N009"/>(or/and <rs type="person" ref="#tillich_person_id__3090">Goya</rs>)
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_9" n="N010"/>5. Optical <rs type="keyword" ref="#Naturalism">naturalism</rs> or <rs type="keyword" ref="#Impressionism">impressionism</rs> (<rs type="person" ref="#tillich_person_id__1343">Monet</rs>)
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_10" n="N011"/>6. American <rs type="keyword" ref="#Naturalism">naturalism</rs> (<rs type="person" ref="#tillich_person_id__926">Homer</rs>?)
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_11" n="N012"/>7. <rs type="person" ref="#tillich_person_id__406">Courbet</rs> (<rs type="person" ref="#tillich_person_id__2574">Corot</rs>)
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_12" n="N013"/>8. <rs type="person" ref="#tillich_person_id__1580">Rembrandt</rs> old man or woman. (Beyond the categories)
            </p>
            <pb facs="#facs_3" n="TLx-0021_p003.jpg" xml:id="img_0003"/>
            <p facs="#facs_3_r">
               <lb facs="#facs_3_l" n="N001"/><rs type="keyword" ref="#Expressionism">expressive </rs>[regarding 1., 2., 3.]
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_3_tr_1">
               <lb facs="#facs_3_l_19" n="N001"/>[3]
               <lb facs="#facs_3_tr_1_tl_1" n="N002"/><hi style="text-decoration: underline;">III. African-Asian analogies</hi>
